<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-02-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-02-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="836" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d836">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Baron
                                    <persName type="to">Fava</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-02-15"><hi rend="italic">February 15,
                                    1900</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 557.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I regret to find that your note of
                            January 15 last, in further reference to the case of the lynching of
                            persons of Italian origin at Tallulah, La., and with which you inclosed
                            a report from the acting consul at New Orleans, was, through an
                            unaccountable oversight, not acknowledged at the time of its
                            receipt.</p>
                        <p>Copy of your note, with its inclosure, was, however, immediately sent to
                            the governor of Louisiana with appropriate commendation to his
                            excellency’s early and attentive notice.</p>
                        <p>Be pleased to accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>